defaultadvantagesdefault? 
default&#xa0;
default1.2.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevolution can 
defaultmean that transport expenditure decisions are made closer and more accountable to those local communities most affected by them. Local authorities are particularly accountable
default -
default although LEPs and LTBs, whilst local, are less directly accountable to local r
defaultesidents
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal organisations should better-understand the needs of their areas, and be better-able to identify and promote transport investment in pursuit of local ends 
defaultthan a national transport department can. In particular, local organisations should b
defaulte able to deploy
default transport investment in pursuit of wider social, economic and environmental goals
default – transport is a means to an end, after all
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.2.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe reduction in the number of separate funding pots and streams for local transport is to be welcomed, as are 
defaultmulti-year funding settlements. These should provide local bodies with more flexibility and certainty as a basis on which to plan to meet local needs and opportunities – instead of responding to central government’s often-changing priorities and criteria
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.2.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultReducing central government’s role may lead to investments being identified, appraised, approved and delivered more quickly.
default&#xa0;
default1.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat are the 
defaultdisadvantagesdefault? 
default&#xa0;
default1.3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultICE has long called for a comprehensive national transport strategy for England. The 
defaultcurrent l
defaultack of national 
default(and now also
default regional
default)
default strategy means that decisions and schemes may exist without much regard for broader context, and the total of local schemes may not 
defaultsum to a commensurate contribution to broader goals (e.g. 
defaultnational connectivity
default,
default 
defaultemi
defaultssions reduction
default)
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal area boundaries (whether local authority, LEP or LTB) can be quite small and organisations not well-equipped to understand or deal with some important travel patterns and corridors which have a larger-than-local focus. It may also
default be that the optimum transport interventions may actually be outside the local area(s) which stand to benefit most, or span more than one area – a very local approach may be less well-suited to dealing with these
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn six of England’s largest metropolitan 
defaultareas (outside London)
default Integrated Transport Authorities 
default(ITAs) 
default(supported by Passenger Transport Executives
default (PTEs)
default) exist to address public transport issues across boundaries. While the boundaries of LEPs and LTBs are 
defaultcoterminous with some of these
default, it is
default not the case in all and there may be scope for confusion and conflict between bodies with overlapping powers, boundaries and objectives
default.
default More generally, the overlapping boundaries of many LEPs (LTB boundaries do not overlap) may give rise to added confusi
defaulton
default&#xa0;
default1.3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe skills and resources available to smaller local bodies are sometimes limited, meaning that specialist knowledge and economies of scale may not be available. In addition, preparation of local major transport schemes requires considerable input of ti
defaultme and effort. In competitive bidding situations (as opposed to the situation with formulaic allocations) considerable resources may be expended for no reward.
default&#xa0;
default1.3.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt may be difficult for national transport bodies (such as the Highways Agency and Network 
defaultRail) to engage effectively with a large number of disparate and competing interests
default.
default 
defaultIt is unclear how that the funding periods for local transport allocations will align with those of Network Rail and the reformed Highways Agency – this may hinder co-ord
defaultination
default of activity for maximum effect.
default&#xa0;
default1.3.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe relatively modest funding available means that each transport body will only be able to promote 
defaultone or two
default medium-sized projects in each funding period. CENTRO, the West Midlands PTE, estimate that a £20 million
default scheme is now the largest which could be funded through their major scheme allocations for 2015-19.
default&#xa0;
default1.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAre there 
defaultbetter modelsdefault?
default&#xa0;
default1.4.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultICE believes it is not yet possible to assess the effectiveness of the new arrangements yet – they have not had enough time to 
defaultmature
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.4.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe do not believe that there is an optimum ‘one size fits all’ model but for larger metropolitan areas, ICE favours 
defaultan 
defaultapproach similar to 
defaultTfL. This offers a
default comprehensive, integrated 
defaultorganisation 
defaultwith assured funding and 
default– experience in London su
defaultggests – can be 
defaultparticularly effective where there are multiple modes and choices and less reliance on private cars
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.4.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCombined Authorities (CAs) are a step in the right direction, particularly in linking transport with land use and economic development pla
defaultnning but may not be appropriate for all 
defaultlocations and still lack some of the important powers and accountability of the London model
default.
default&#xa0;
default1.4.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe pooling of large amounts of transport funding in the SLGF (into which LEPs bid) makes the potential contribution of 
defaultLTBs less clear.
default&#xa0;
default1.4.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn all discussions of changes to funding criteria and streams, the total sum of funds available for local transport must be taken into account. Expenditure available for local transport, particularly capital, has been greatly reduced.
default&#xa0;
default1.4.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlso important when considering the merits of changing from one model to another are the costs associated with institutional and policy change. The disruption, uncertainty and delay incurred as a result of (all) governments
default’
default re-organisation
defaults
default can be conside
defaultrable – this argument
default, and the benefits of stability and certainty,
default seems to have been long-accepted in rail policy,
default and
default now also for the Strategic Road Network – but not 
defaultyet 
defaultfor 
defaultlocal transport.
