default2.1.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultICE’s experience is that capacity levels are v
defaultery
default, and perhaps increasingly,
default variable
default. L
defaultarger local authorities 
default(particularly counties and larger unitaries) 
defaultand 
defaultITAs/
defaultPTEs
default will generally have sufficient skilled staff for most transport-related tasks – although this is increasingly uncertain
default as local funding is squeezed
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.1.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultS
defaultmaller local authorities 
defaultare less to have sufficient capacity. ICE’s consultations around the country (
defaultas part of our ‘State of the Nation’ project) suggests that pressure on local authority budgets leading to headcount reductions threatens the capacity of smaller authorities to manage transport projects and programmes
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.1.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe capacity of 
defaultLEPs 
defaultand
default LTBs 
defaultis 
defaultheavily influenced by their local authority and ITA/PTE partners. Few of the new bodies employ transport specialists, or have delivery responsibility or capability themselves.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat would the 
defaultoptimum delivery bodydefault look like?
default&#xa0;
default2.2.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs noted, we do not believe 
defaultthere is a
default single best model but 
defaultthe TfL 
defaultintegrated model 
defaultis 
defaultwell-suited to larger urban areas with multiple modes. Combined Authorities go some way towards this model but still fall short
default, lacking such clear democratic oversight and control over some 
defaultimpo
defaultrtant subjects
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultVery local bodies 
defaultare 
defaultunlikely to have the strategic view or depth and breadth of skills required – an ideal model is likely to be “larger-than-local” at least
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.2.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe consider that - in view of the diverse nature of the England’s local 
defaultgeographies - it may be
default more useful to think in terms of an optimum skillset 
defaultand range of attributes 
defaultrather than 
defaulta single model
default. It is our experience, for example, that skills 
defaultin programme management
default are in short supply across a range of organisation types
default.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default3.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMajor transport schemes can often
default span local authority
default boundaries and the wider sub-region, at least, needs to be considered.  Even this can be too small scale – cross-region issues frequently arise in the Midlands, 
defaultfor example
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultEnsuring co-operation among bodies can be difficult. The temptation to parochialism 
defaultmay be strong and some areas - and perhaps particularly their 
defaultLEPs 
default- 
defaultmay see themselves as being in competition
default (indeed the Growth Fund encourages this)
default. It shouldn’t be a 
default‘zero sum game’ but it is a considerable risk
default that it will be seen as such
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA mechanism akin to the 
default‘Duty to Co-operate’
default which compels local planning authorities to work with their neighbours may be worth considering for 
defaulttransport organisation
defaults. 
defaultAlternatively, some kind of regional process could also work, although any ‘top down’ or regional structure is unlikely to find favour with the current government.
default&#xa0;
default3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs previously noted, the ITA/PTE and TfL models exist to deal with schemes across metropoli
defaulttan borough boundaries
default – a sensible approach in our view.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default4.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe feedback we have received suggests a mixed picture, reflecting the varied
default maturity of local arrangements, the diverse nature of the areas, and - invariably - the personalities involved.
default&#xa0;
default4.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe are aware of some tensions between local organisations and national ones - the Highways Agency and Network Rail. 
defaultT
defaulthis may be inevitable
default to 
defaultsome extent
default as there are often likely to be more local demands than can be met by national agencies. Loss of the regional tier of governance has removed one level of mediation 
defaultand sifting of bids 
defaultbetween local and national organisations (although there cou
defaultld be friction between local and regional too, of course).
default&#xa0;
default4.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultReform of the Highways Agency provides two important relevant opportunities in this context:
default&#xa0;
default4.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal authorities often feel that the relationship with the Department for Transport is unnecessarily top-down and micro-managed. 
defaultRecent changes may see a reduction day-to-day micro-management (such as competitive funding bids requiring very rapid
default responses) but will also see a confusing
default superstructure of LEPs and LTBs centrally-imposed.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default5.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe have major concerns that the reduced scale of funds available for all local transport is insufficient. In our recent engagem
defaultent around England as part of our 2014 ‘State of the Nation’ development process, the level and certainty of future funding for local transport (roads and public transport, capital and revenue) has repeatedly featured as one of the greatest concerns across
default all infrastructure issues
default.
default&#xa0;
default5.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe welcome the intention to simplify funding streams, and reduce the 
defaultnumber of separate competitions.
default&#xa0;
default5.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultICE broadly welcomed decision
defaults
default in recent years to replace the competitive bidding process for “Integrated Transport and Main
defaulttenance” with – firstly, in December 2010 – an indicative allocation, and then – in September 2012 – the decision to devolve the decision-making process for local major transport schemes. ICE believes that decisions should be made close to those most affec
defaultted by them. We also believe that competitive bidding does not always lead to the desired outcomes (it can favours those best at bidding, rather than the greatest need, and may militate against balanced programmes of expenditure (including maintenance))
default.
default&#xa0;
default5.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe more recent decision to allocate large amounts of funding to the SLGF causes us concerns over whether transport needs will be adequately resource
defaultd
default, and causes us (and others) some confusion as to the future role of the LTBs
default.
default&#xa0;
default5.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe are unclear how 
defaulteffectively the proposed allocation schedules will fit with Network Rail’s and the Highways Agency’s current and proposed funding and programming arrangements
default.
default&#xa0;
default5.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTaking a broad view of local transport expenditure, we are concerned that the ring-fencing of 
defaultconcessionary fares budgets may be distorting local public transport support spending.  ADEPT recently reported
default that councils are spending 65%-75% of their public transport budgets on concessionary fares.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default6.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultICE believes that 
defaultit makes sense for transport issues to be considered alongside the many other issues that impact on economic growth in local areas, and 
defaultfor 
defaultfunding t
defaulto be prioritised accordingly
default. However, as with other questions, it is 
defaulttoo early to say 
defaultwith certainty how the new arrangements will work in practice.
default&#xa0;
default6.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is 
defaultessential that the full impact of transport investment or disinvestment on economic growth is 
defaultproperly considered when local decisions are being taken
default. This requires that 
defaultpartnerships must have access to the appropriate skills and knowledge, and it isn’t clear whether this will be the case
default with regard to transport investment.
default&#xa0;
default6.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA 44% top slicing of 
defaultIntegrated Transport Block funding into the 
defaultSGLF
default seems disproportionate relative to other contribution sources.
default&#xa0;
default6.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFrom our engagement with members and partner organisations, there seems to be widespread uncertainty as to the future role of the LTBs.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;
default7.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal transport has traditionally relied heavily on
default straightforward public sector grant funding. With the reduction in such resources available for local transport (in contrast to rail and the Strategic Road Network), local organisations have much incentive to seek alternative sources
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome alternative so
defaulturces are well-established; others are only emerging, or have yet to be adopted. It is unclear to us that alternative sources could compensate for reductions in public funding in the short-medium term – although they will be important for specific purposes
default and in specific locations
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal planning authorities have long been able to secure developer contributions for infrastructure improvements through Section 106 of the Planning Act (and its predecessors). Such contributions are a well-established principl
defaulte but only available in specific circumstances. Recent tightening of the criteria, their application and the ability and willingness of developers to contribute in a difficult economic climate mean that Section 106 is unlikely to assume much greater import
defaultance in future.
default&#xa0;
default7.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAlso planning-related, the Community Infrastructure Levy (CIL) offers opportunities to use developer contributions more flexibly than Section 106. Introduction of CIL (as with Section 106) appears to favour economically stronger locations 
defaultwhere there is more development interest and value
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCrossrail
default is an excellent example of how private funding can be secured for transport investment – it uses CIL, business rate supplements and other developer contributions to provide a large share of the project’s funds. It is unlikely that many projects not servin
defaultg high-value locations in London could put together such a package, however
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGovernment has, and seeks to continue to, broaden the uses to which CIL might be put. For example, the new National Infrastructure Plan suggests that CIL might be used to fund 
defaultdi
defaultrect compensation to individuals affected by development. While this may be a worthwhile use, it does dilute CIL’s original purpose
default by reducing the sums available for new infrastructure
default. The ICE warned in 2011, during the passage of the Localism Bill, that
default CIL might simply become a tax on development – this appears to be coming to pass
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCity Deals have included a number of mechanisms for securing private sector funding for local infrastructure investment. Greater Manchester’s ‘Earn Back’ scheme is of parti
defaultcular interest, allowing the area to capture the increases in tax contributions generated by infrastructure investment
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTax Increment Financing (TIF) models, which have some similarities with ‘Earn Back’ are being investigated for use in England. 
defaultIn the U
defaultK, 
defaultScotland has pioneered this approach, although not without some difficulty
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSome areas, notably West Yorkshire, have pursued infrastructure funds using small Council Tax levies or combinations of other incomes (such as CIL or S106) to lever additional 
defaultprivate finance. However, this source may be at risk with recent announcements from the Department for Communities and Loca
defaultl Government on limits to annual
default increases in local taxation.
default&#xa0;
default7.10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultA clear income stream is important to attract private sector investors
default. This may be more difficult to demonstrate in local transport – typically roads – than is the case for most utilities. Attempts to introduce road user charging or tolls (such as in Manchester and Edinburgh) have failed. Workplace parking levies have been 
defaultintroduced in Nottingham but Bristol shelved plans for its own scheme
default.
default&#xa0;
default7.11.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe above examples are merely a selection. It is clear that there are an increasing number of alternative funding options open to local authorities. These are valuable and should be pu
defaultrsued but it remains unclear how widely applicable they are, and the extent to which they can compensate for reductions in mainstream public funding.
default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default8.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAccountability is becoming less clear. With the abolition of the RDAs, local authorities were generally responsible for local transport – notwithstanding that they have modest influence over the rail network or commercial (de-regulated) bus services. Large
default metropolitan areas dealt with public transport issues through ITAs/PTEs, although local roads remained the concern of individual councils
default.
default&#xa0;
default8.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe introduction of CAs, while welcome from a strategic policy perspective, has given rise to some uncertainties ab
defaultout accountability – these might already have existed around ITAs/PTEs to some extent but the broader focus of the CAs widens this question
default.
default&#xa0;
default8.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe introduction of LEPs, in particular, gives rise to uncertainty about local accountability. It is likely that 
defaultsome will establish clearer and more accountable procedures than others.
